<div align="center"><table width="80%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
<tr><td>
<a name="Identification">
<b>Identification</b></td></tr><tr><td>
Extracted from: Coelho, B. W. T., 2004. A review of the bee genus Augochlorella (Hymenoptera: Halictidae: Augochlorini). Systematic Entomology, Vol. 29. 282-323. 
<p> 
Female. Size. (1) Total body length 5–6 mm; (2) forewing 
length 3–4 mm. Structure. (3) Head slightly wider than long, head length to width ratio 1.11–1.15; (4) elevation of labrum 
with apex orbicular, protuberant and diameter about 1/3 of 
upper margin length of labrum; (5) F10 about 2.5 length 
of F1; (6) preoccipital ridge carinate; (7) pronotal lateral 
angle obtuse, anterolateral margin in dorsal view gently 
concave; (8) anterior mesoscutal border broadly rounded; 
(9) basal area of propodeum about 1.5 longer than metanotum; (10) basal area of propodeum crescentic-shaped in 
outiline from dorsal view; (11) posterior margin of basal 
area of propodeum distinct and abruptly rounded, surface 
flat when viewed from side; (12) length and width of posterior surface of propodeum approximately equal; (13) tegula 
oval, length to width ratio 1.5–1.6. Sculpture. (14) Upper 
paraocular closely punctate, becoming more sparsely punctured (i ¼ d) in lower paraocular area, surface between 
punctures usually smooth; (15) supraclypeal area sparsely 
punctured medially, becoming more densely punctured peripherally in lower half, surface between punctures predominantly smooth; (16) clypeus area with punctures irregular in 
size and spacing, smaller and closer at margins of clypeus 
compared to centre, distal third of clypeus usually with 
several somewhat elongate, coarse puctures separated by 
smooth ground; (17) mesoscutum with contiguous punctures, slightly coarser than those of frons, about anterior fourth of scutum finely transversely strigose; (18) scutellum 
with contiguous punctures, slightly finer and more irregular 
than those of mesoscutum, surface weakly roughened; (19) 
tegula without conspicuous punctures, surface between 
punctures smooth; (20) pre-episternum coarsely and densely 
rugose-punctate; (21) mesepisternum more finely rugosepunctate than pre-episternum; (22) basal area of propodeum with carinae very irregular and branching medially, 
straight at extreme lateral corners, extending full length of 
basal area; (23) posterior surface of propodeum granular 
and densely punctured, with fine, round punctures and 
scattered coarser hair bases intermixed, surface usually 
dominated by strong microstriae; (24) lateral surface of 
propodeum strongly microstriated, coarser than microstriae 
of posterior surface of propodeum, with scattered large hair 
bases; (25) anterior surface of T1 with fine punctures, separated by 1–2 puncture widths and scattered coarser hair 
bases intermix, ground between punctures lineolate; (26) 
dorsal surface of T1 with fine punctures, separated by 
about 2 puncture widths in central area of transversely 
lineolate ground, depressed marginal area weak with narrow smooth band along edge. Colour. Bright green, median 
region of face with crimson-violaceous reflections, except: 
(27) mandible usually with base blackish, light brown becoming reddish apically; (28) entire clypeus blackish to 
brown, sometimes upper corners metallic green with violet 
highlights; (29) antenna dark brown, scape darker than the 
rest, flagellum slightly lighter below than above; (30) legs 
brown, fore femur sometimes with green highlights; (31) 
sterna brown; (32) metasomal terga brown, greenish laterally, posterior marginal zones with narrow translucent 
brown edges. Pubescence. (33) Dorsal surface with very 
short, fine, highly plumose light brown to whitish hairs; 
long, simple or branched light brown to whitish hairs on 
nearly all body parts; hairs of outer surfaces of mid and 
hind tibiae brown in some lights. 
<p> 
Male (the only specimen is headless). Size. (1) Total body 
length (estimated for head) 6 mm; (2) forewing length 
3.6 mm. Structure. (34m) hind basitarsus with ventral convexity on second fourth; (35m) surface of hind tibia gently 
convex; (36m) apical margin of S4 bilobed with small emargination between lobes, emargination with row of short 
marginal hairs, lateral ones longer than median ones; 
(37m) anal lip of proctiger with 14 long postanal filaments, 
closely placed and densely setose, lateral filaments 1.5 as 
long as median ones; (38m) spiculum narrow; (39m) apical 
margin of S8 straight, without apical setae; (40m) apical 
margin of S7 with median process, with 6 setae. Genitalia. 
(41m) gonobasal dorsal lobes weakly projecting over gonocoxites; (42m) small membranous parapenial lobes present; 
(43m) basal process of gonostylus present, without setae; 
(44m) inner lobe of ventral gonostylus with projection 
divided, double margin of different height, inner margin 
higher than outer margin, bearing row of about 8 flattened 
and long setae, outer margin bearing row of about 7 setae, 
at inner extremity about 4 setae longer than other ones; 
(45m) outer lobe of ventral gonostylus with about 9 setae 
shorter than those of inner ventral lobe; (46m) dorsal process of gonostylus sclerotized, lobe divided into 3 projections – 
basal shorter and narrower than others, and median with 
wider extremity than superior; (47m) penis valve markedly 
expanded laterally, with internal extremity curved upwards, 
median dorsal ridge strongly convex in profile view and 
with orifice in apex, marginal depression on inner side; 
(48m) volsella with triangular basal area longer than apical, 
angular internal apex projecting in ventral direction. Sculpture. 
(21) mesepisternum with coarse oblique punctures separated by 1–2 puncture widths or less of irregularly roughened ground in lower area; (23) posterior surface of 
propodeum rugose-punctate; (24) lateral surface of propodeum more strongly rugose-punctate than posterior surface; 
(25) anterior surface of T1 with scattered coarse hair bases, 
surface between punctures lineolate; (26) dorsal surface of 
T1 with fine, but strong punctures, separated by about one 
puncture width, surface between punctures lineolate. 
Colour. Mesosoma green with strong copper highlights; 
(30) legs dark brown to brown, coxae, femora and middle 
trochanter with faint green metallic highlights (31) sterna 
dark brown; (32) metasomal terga coppery with few faint 
green highlights laterally and on anterior surface of T1. 
Pubescence. (51m) hind femur with distal ventral tuft of about 7 simple, large hairs, separated in groups of 5 and 2 
hairs together, as long as ventral margin of femur; (52m) 
hairs on under surface of hind tibia much shorter than 
diameter of tibia except about 3 hairs at distal part nearly 
as long as tibial spur; (53m) lower convexity of hind 
basitarsus with row of about 5 simple, large hairs, about 
2 longer than width of basitarsus (convexity excluded). 
<p> 
Distribution. This species is found in Brazil in the states of 
Parana´, Santa Catarina and Rio Grande do Sul (Fig. 15). 
</td></tr><tr><td><br></td></tr>
